From article <ian.736040672@bvsd.Co.EDU>, by ian@bvsd.Co.EDU (Ian S. Nelson):
>>: I have seen various references to 'triple des' recently. Could anyone
>>: tell me what it is ?
> I think you take a block, encrypt it with key a, decrypt it with key b and
> re-encrypt it with key a.

You either double the effective key length with
	C = E(K1, D(K2, E(K1,M)));

or triple the key with
	C = E(K3, D(K2, E(K1,M)));

The first method is considered "more" compatible with plain 
(single) DES (you just set K1=K2)...Beats me, why it's 
easier, than K3=K1. (:-)
